          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>When insulin binds to its receptor on a muscle cell, what is the immediate cellu</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>When insulin binds to its receptor on a muscle cell, what is the immediate cellular response?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>ATP production by mitochondria increases</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>ATP production is a mitochondrial function and is not the direct response triggered by insulin receptor binding.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Glucose transporters move to the cell surface</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. When insulin binds its receptor, glucose transporter proteins are mobilised to the cell membrane, allowing glucose to enter the cell. This is why insulin deficiency in diabetes prevents cellular glucose uptake.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sodium ions are actively pumped out of the cell</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sodium ion transport is handled by the Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase pump, which operates independently of insulin signalling.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lysosomes release digestive enzymes into the cytoplasm</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lysosomal enzyme release is not related to insulin signalling. Lysosomes degrade waste material within their own acidic compartment.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "When insulin binds its receptor on muscle cells, glucose transporters reach the cell surface, enabling glucose entry. This is the cell signalling example described in the video."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Insulin binding triggers the translocation of glucose transporters to the membrane surface — this is the mechanism impaired in diabetes mellitus."
                }
              ],
